ari under the guidance of Tulunadan expert and master Chekavar, Aringodar.\n\nChandu has to recount only losses in his life, as Aromal ensures his sister is not married to Chandu. He even deceives Chandu by usurping and marrying Kunjinooli (Chithra), who was in love with Chandu. The heartbroken Chandu moves ahead and continues to master the art of Kalari Payattu from Aringodar.\n\nOn wedding day of Aromal, Unniyarcha invites Chandu to her room. However Unniyarcha\u2019s husband, the eunuch Kunjiraman sees them. Unniyarcha, the clever vixen that she is, convinces her husband that Chandu broke into her room as she was awaiting the arrival of Kunjiraman. Chandu gets a sobriquet: 'Womanizer Chandu.' A dejected Chandu finds solace in Kunji, Aringodar\u2019s daughter.\n\nFeudal lord Unnichandror (Ramu) arrives at the footsteps of Aringodar and invites him to represent his cause in an angam (duel unto death) against mooppu feud with his brother Unnikonar. Unnikonar, in turn, invites Aromal to represent him. Chandu is now caught in a dilemma, when his uncle requests him to play second hand to Aromal in the angam against his teacher Aringodar. Unniyarcha also appears and offers to live with Chandu if he assists Aromal to win against Aringodar. A tempted Chandu, decides to second Aromal. Chandu takes on the task of revitalizing Aromal's swords by providing them for treatment to the blacksmith. However, Kunji, Aringodar\u2019s daughter, bribes the blacksmith and makes them brittle.\n\nOn the day of the duel, Aromal, though highly skilled, is no match for the master Aringodar. To add to the misery, Aromal's sword breaks in two. As Chandu placates an attacking Aringodar, seeking time to replace the weapon, Aringodar obliges. Then wily Aromal throws his broken sword and kills an unguarded Aringodar.\n\nAromal is declared winner. As he retires to his resting place, Chandu follows him to tend to his injuries. Aromal blames Chandu of cheating, by treating the swords to make them brittle, and attacks him. Aromal kills himself in an accident by falling over a lamp. As people gather, Aromal breathes out his last words: \"Chandu betrayed us!\".\n\nThe ill-fated Chandu escapes the mob and finds the blacksmith, who informs that he was bribed by Kunji. Fighting his way through the entire contingent of guards, Chandu storms into Aringodar's household seeking Kunji. To add to his list of regrets, he finds Kunji has committed suicide by hanging herself. Chandu returns to Puthooram Veedu and is greeted by a raging Unniyarcha, who vows her sons will avenge her brother\u2019s death.\n\nYears later, Aromal Unni and Kannapan Unni (sons of Unniyarcha and Aromal Chekavar respectively) come to the kalari of Arangodar seeking revenge. Chandu explains to them the situation, hoping to avoid a duel. However, after being repeatedly challenge Chandu easily beats both, once again showing his mastery. Thinking they will leave before bloodshed is inevitable he attempts to retire his weapons. The two young warriors are in no mood to leave in defeat and insist on a duel to the death. Chandu plainly tells them about their mistakes in the duel and skillfully explains the possible strategies they have up their sleeve. Aromal Unni announces himself, \"I, son of Unniyarcha, will die or go back with your head.\" Chandu realises the madness in the youngsters and appears to relent to their provocations, turns his back to them as if to pray in preparation for the duel. But knowing that no one will ever be able to win against him, and reminded that Aromal is Kannappan Chekavar's grandson, he commits one final act of valour: Chandu stabs himself with his sword. \"You would have been my son,\" he tells Aromal Unni reminiscing bitterly on what could have been. He reaches out to the statue of his deity and dies. There ends life of a valiant but misunderstood man, the greatest warrior of his age.\n\n== Cast ==\n\n*[[Mammootty]] as [[Chandu Chekavar]]: A misunderstood hero belonging to a mercenary clan. The orphan boy, Chandu, a quick learner, earns the love and admiration of his uncle, while he is loathed by his cousin. Veteran actor [[Prem Nazir]] was originally considered for this role but since MT felt Mammootty's physique would better suit the character.<ref>K. T. C. Abdullah, P. M. Jayan. [http://www.chandrikadaily.com/contentspage.aspx?id=29699 \"\u0d35\u0d1f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d28\u0d4d\u200d \u0d35\u0d40\u0d30\u0d17\u0d3e\u0d25\u0d2f\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d4d\u200d \u0d06\u0d26\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d02 \u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d47\u0d02\u0d28\u0d38\u0d40\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d \u0d06\u0d2f\u0d3f\u0d30\u0d41\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d41 \u0d28\u0d3e\u0d2f\u0d15\u0d28\u0d4d\u200d\"]. ''Chandrika Weekly''. 7 October 2013. Retrieved 29 March 2014.</ref> \n*[[Balan K. Nair]] as Kannappan Chekavar: Chandu's uncle and a veteran master of the southern style of Kalari martial arts. He adopts Chandu when the boy loses both his parents and brings him to Puthooram to live and learn with his cousins. \n*[[Suresh Gopi]] as [[Aromal Chekavar]]: son of Kannappan Chekavar.\n*[[Madhavi (actress)|Madhavi]] as [[Unniarcha]]: A [[succubus]] and vixen warrior, sister of Aromal Chekavar and fianc\u00e9e of Chandu Chekavar.\n*[[Captain Raju]] as Aringodar Chekavar: A mighty legend and master of northern Kalari known as \"Thulunadan Kalari\" and Chandu's second teacher in his lifelong learning discipline.\n*[[Geetha (actress)|Geetha]] as Kunji\n*[[Rajalakshmi (actress)|Rajalakshmi]] as Kuttimani\n*[[Jomol]] as young Unniarcha\n*[[Vineeth Kumar]] as young Chandu\n*Vishal menon as young Kunhiraman\n*[[Biyon]] as  Child Artist\n*[[Ramu (actor)|Ramu]]  as Unnichandror\n*[[Devan (actor)|Devan]] as Unnikonnar\n*[[Oduvil Unnikrishnan]] as the king\n*[[Chithra (actress)|Chithra]] as Kunjinooli\n*[[Soorya (actress)|Soorya]] as blacksmith's daughter\n*[[Sanjay Mitra (Actor)|Sanjay Mitra]] as Aromalunni \n*[[Rasheed Ummer]] as Kanappanunni\n*[[Sukumari]] as Kannappa Chekavar's wife\n*[[V. K. Sreeraman]] as Kunhiraman\n*[[Kundara Johny]] as Aringodar's student\n*[[Bheeman Raghu]] as Aringodar's student\n*Tony as Unnikannan\n\n== Reception ==\nOru Vadakkan Veeragatha received both commercial and critical acclaim.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/happy-birthday-mammookka-mammootty-oru-vadakkan-veeragatha-pazhassi-raja/1/758446.html|title=Happy Birthday Mammootty: 5 best performances of Mammukka you shouldn't miss|access-date=27 December 2017}}</ref> In a 2013 online poll, [[IBN Live]] listed ''Oru Vadakkan Veeragatha'' as the third greatest Indian film of all time. The poll was conducted as part of the celebrations of Indian cinema completing 100 years. The poll constituted a list of 100 films from different Indian languages.<ref name=IBN1>[http://ibnlive.in.com/news/mayabazar-is-indias-greatest-film-ever-ibnlive-poll/391184-8-66.html \"'Mayabazar' is India's greatest film ever: IBNLive poll\"] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6W5lwHhfU?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20150204142913/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/mayabazar-is-indias-greatest-film-ever-ibnlive-poll/391184-8-66.html |date=4 February 2015 }}. [[IBN Live]]. 12 May 2013. Retrieved 24 May 2013.</ref><ref name=IBN2>[http://ibnlive.in.com/news/ibnlive-poll-vote-for-indias-greatest-film-of-all-time/387871-8.html \"IBNLive Poll: Vote for India's greatest film of all time\"]. [[IBN Live]]. 26 April 2013. Retrieved 24 May 2013.</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\nThe film's soundtrack contains 5 hit songs, all composed by [[Bombay Ravi]]. Lyrics by [[Kaithapram]] and [[K. Jayakumar]].\n\n{| border=\"10\" cellpadding=\"10\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! # !! Title !! Singer(s)\n|-\n| 1\n| \"Chandanalepa Sugandham\"\n| [[K. J. Yesudas]]\n|-\n| 2\n| \"Enthinavidam\"\n| [[K. J. Yesudas]]\n|-\n| 3\n| \"Indulekha Kanthurannu\"\n| [[K. J. Yesudas]]\n|-\n| 4\n| \"Kalarivilakku Thelinjathaano\"\n| [[K. S. Chitra]]\n|-\n| 5\n| \"Unni Ganapathi Thamburaane\"\n| [[K. S. Chitra]], [[Asha Latha]]\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n'''[[National Film Awards]]'''\n*[[National Film Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screenplay]] \u2013 [[M. T. Vasudevan Nair]]\n*[[National Film Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] \u2013 [[Mammootty]] <small>(also for ''[[Mathilukal]]'')</small>\n*[[National Film Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]] \u2013 [[P. Krishnamoorthy]]\n*[[National Film Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]] \u2013 P. Krishnamoorthy\n\n'''[[Filmfare Awards South]]'''\n*[[Filmfare Award for Best Film \u2013 Malayalam]] \u2013 [[P. V. Gangadharan]]\n\n'''[[Kerala State Film Awards]]'''\n*[[Kerala State Film Award for Best Popular Film|Best Popular Film]]\n*[[Kerala State Film Award for Best Screenplay|Best Screen Play]] \u2013 [[M. T. Vasudevan Nair]]\n*[[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] \u2013 [[Mammootty]]\n*[[Kerala State Film Award for Second Best Actress|Second Best Actress]] \u2013 [[Geetha (actress)|Geetha]]\n*[[Kerala State Film Award for Best Photography|Best Cinematography]] \u2013 K. Ramachandra Babu\n*[[Kerala State Film Award for Best Singer|Best Female Play Back Singer]] \u2013 [[K. S. Chithra]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0230597|title=Oru Vadakkan Veeragatha}}\n* [http://movieraga.indulekha.com/2012/09/04/relook-oru-vadakkan-veeragatha/ movieraga.indulekha.com&nbsp;\u2013 \u0d35\u0d40\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d41\u0d02 \u0d12\u0d30\u0d41 \u0d35\u0d1f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d28\u0d4d\u200d\u0d35\u0d40\u0d30\u0d17\u0d3e\u0d25]\n{{Hariharan (director)}}\n\n[[Category:Indian martial arts films]]\n[[Category:1980s Malayalam-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Kalarippayattu films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by M. T. Vasudevan Nair]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Hariharan]]\n[[Category:Indian epic films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actor National Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films whose production designer won the Best Production Design National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Costume Design National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Original Screenplay National Film Award]]\n[[Category:1989 martial arts films]]\n", "name_user": "Fylindfotberserk", "label": "safe", "comment": "Generalformattingbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oru_Vadakkan_Veeragatha"}
{"title_page": "Alessandro Bianchi (footballer, born 1966)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Alessandro Bianchi\n| fullname = \n| image = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|4|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Cervia]], Italy\n| height = 1.74 m\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1983\u20131988\n| clubs1 = [[A.C. Cesena|Cesena]]\n| caps1 = 40\n| goals1 = 3\n| years2 = 1986\u20131987\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Calcio Padova|Padova]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 28\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 1988\u20131996\n| clubs3 = [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]]\n| caps3 = 178\n| goals3 = 9\n| years4 = 1996\u20132001\n| clubs4 = Cesena\n| caps4 = 130\n| goals4 = 1\n| totalcaps = 376\n| totalgoals = 13\n| nationalyears1 = 1992\u20131993\n| nationalteam1 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 9\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1 = \n| managerclubs1 = \n}}\n\n'''Alessandro Bianchi''' ({{IPA-it|ales\u02c8sandro \u02c8bja\u014bki}}; born 7 April 1966) is an Italian former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]] or as [[Forward (association football)|forward]], in the position of [[Midfielder#Winger|right winger]].\n\n==Club career==\nBianchi spent most of his career with [[A.C. Cesena|Cesena]], making his professional debut during the [[1985\u201386 Serie B|1985\u201386 Serie B season]] and also retiring with the club in 2001, and with [[Internazionale Milano F.C.|Inter]]. He spent the 1986\u201387 season on loan with [[Padova Calcio|Padova]] in [[Serie C]] before returning to Cesena, and he transferred to Inter for 4.5 billion Lit. in 1988. With Inter, he was notably a member of the starting line-up that won the record-breaking [[1988\u201389 Serie A|1988\u201389 Serie A title]], although, despite his talent, a serious muscle injury during the [[1992\u201393 Serie A|1992\u201393 season]] greatly affected his career at the age of 27. He remained at the club until 1996, also winning the [[1989 Supercoppa Italiana]], and two [[UEFA Cup]]s ([[1990\u201391 UEFA Cup|1990\u201391]] and [[1993\u201394 UEFA Cup|1993\u201394]]) during his time at Inter, notably scoring a decisive goal against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in the round of 16 of the 1990\u201391 edition of the UEFA Cup.<ref name=\"Bianchi, Alessandro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filippofabbri.net/articoli/storie-di-calcio/storie-di-calcio-interviste/764-qlala-in-volo-tra-cesena-e-milano.html|title=Bianchi, Alessandro|website=www.filippofabbri.net|language=Italian|author1=Filippo Fabbri|date=23 February 2010|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter his stint with Inter, he returned once again to Cesena in [[1996\u201397 Serie B|Serie B]], where he remained until his retirement from professional football.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttocalciatori.net/Bianchi_Alessandro|title=Alessandro Bianchi|website=www.tuttocalciatori.net|language=Italian|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref> After his retirement, he still remained active as a footballer, and in 2010, he played in the Cervia Over-35 team as a midfielder, and during the 2012\u201313 season, he took part in the Umbro Second Division League with Eugubina Calcio.<ref name=\"Bianchi, Alessandro\"/>\n\n==International career==\nBianchi also represented the [[Italy national football team|Italian national football team]] on 9 occasions between 1992 and 1994. He made his international debut under manager [[Arrigo Sacchi]] on 19 February 1992, in a 4\u20130 international friendly home victory over [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]] in Cesena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=8&squadra=1|title=Convocazioni e presenze in campo: Alessandro Bianchi|website=www.figc.it|publisher=FIGC|language=Italian|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n'''Inter'''<ref name=\"Bianchi, Alessandro\"/>\n*[[Serie A]]: [[1988\u201389 Serie A|1988\u201389]]\n*[[Supercoppa Italiana]]: [[1989 Supercoppa Italiana|1989]]\n*[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]: [[1991 UEFA Cup Final|1990\u201391]], [[1994 UEFA Cup Final|1993\u201394]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{NFT|15436|Alessandro Bianchi}}\n*{{TuttoCalciatori|Bianchi_Alessandro}}\n*[http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=8&squadra=1 Profile at FIGC.it] {{in lang|it}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bianchi, Alessandro}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Serie C players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Cesena players]]\n[[Category:Calcio Padova players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Alessandro Bianchi\n| fullname = \n| image = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1966|4|7|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Cervia]], [[Italy]]\n| height = 1.74 m\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 1983\u20131988\n| years2 = 1986\u20131987\n| years3 = 1988\u20131996\n| years4 = 1996\u20132001\n| clubs1 = [[A.C. Cesena|Cesena]]\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Calcio Padova|Padova]] (loan)\n| clubs3 = [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]]\n| clubs4 = Cesena\n| caps1 = 40\n| caps2 = 28\n| caps3 = 178\n| caps4 = 130\n| goals1 = 3\n| goals2 = 0\n| goals3 = 9\n| goals4 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = 1992\u20131993\n| nationalteam1 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 9\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1 = \n| managerclubs1 = \n| pcupdate = \n| ntupdate = \n}}\n\n'''Alessandro Bianchi''' ({{IPA-it|ales\u02c8sandro \u02c8bja\u014bki}}; born 7 April 1966) is a former [[Italians|Italian]] professional [[Association football|footballer]], who played as a [[midfielder]] or as [[Forward (association football)|forward]], in the position of [[Midfielder#Winger|right winger]].\n\n==Club career==\nBianchi spent most of his career with [[A.C. Cesena|Cesena]], making his professional debut during the [[1985\u201386 Serie B|1985\u201386 Serie B season]] and also retiring with the club in 2001, and with [[Internazionale Milano F.C.|Inter]]. He spent the 1986\u201387 season on loan with [[Padova Calcio|Padova]] in [[Serie C]] before returning to Cesena, and he transferred to Inter for 4.5 billion Lit. in 1988. With Inter, he was notably a member of the starting line-up that won the record-breaking [[1988\u201389 Serie A|1988\u201389 Serie A title]], although, despite his talent, a serious muscle injury during the [[1992\u201393 Serie A|1992\u201393 season]] greatly affected his career at the age of 27. He remained at the club until 1996, also winning the [[1989 Supercoppa Italiana]], and two [[UEFA Cup]]s ([[1990\u201391 UEFA Cup|1990\u201391]] and [[1993\u201394 UEFA Cup|1993\u201394]]) during his time at Inter, notably scoring a decisive goal against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in the round of 16 of the 1990\u201391 edition of the UEFA Cup.<ref name=\"Bianchi, Alessandro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filippofabbri.net/articoli/storie-di-calcio/storie-di-calcio-interviste/764-qlala-in-volo-tra-cesena-e-milano.html|title=Bianchi, Alessandro|website=www.filippofabbri.net|language=Italian|author1=Filippo Fabbri|date=23 February 2010|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter his stint with Inter, he returned once again to Cesena in [[1996\u201397 Serie B|Serie B]], where he remained until his retirement from professional football.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttocalciatori.net/Bianchi_Alessandro|title=Alessandro Bianchi|website=www.tuttocalciatori.net|language=Italian|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref> After his retirement, he still remained active as a footballer, and in 2010, he played in the Cervia Over-35 team as a midfielder, and during the 2012\u201313 season, he took part in the Umbro Second Division League with Eugubina Calcio.<ref name=\"Bianchi, Alessandro\"/>\n\n==International career==\nBianchi also represented the [[Italy national football team|Italian national football team]] on 9 occasions between 1992 and 1994. He made his international debut under manager [[Arrigo Sacchi]] on 19 February 1992, in a 4\u20130 international friendly home victory over [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]] in Cesena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=8&squadra=1|title=Convocazioni e presenze in campo: Alessandro Bianchi|website=www.figc.it|publisher=FIGC|language=Italian|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n;Inter<ref name=\"Bianchi, Alessandro\"/>\n*[[Serie A]]: [[1988\u201389 Serie A|1988\u201389]]\n*[[Supercoppa Italiana]]: [[1989 Supercoppa Italiana|1989]]\n*[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]: [[1991 UEFA Cup Final|1990\u201391]], [[1994 UEFA Cup Final|1993\u201394]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{NFT|15436|Alessandro Bianchi}}\n*{{TuttoCalciatori|Bianchi_Alessandro}}\n*[http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=8&squadra=1 Profile at FIGC.it] {{in lang|it}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bianchi, Alessandro}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Serie C players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Cesena players]]\n[[Category:Calcio Padova players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Cup winning players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add totalcaps and totalgoals. Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alessandro_Bianchi_(footballer,_born_1966)"}
{"title_page": "Reapers Stakes", "text_new": "{{short description|Defunct American Thoroughbred horse race}}\n{{Infobox horseraces\n| class         = Discontinued stakes\n| horse race    = Reapers Stakes\n| website       = \n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| location      = [[Sheepshead Bay Race Track]]<br>[[Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| inaugurated   = 1887 - 1907\n| race type     = [[Thoroughbred]] - [[Flat racing]]\n| distance      = {{frac|1|3|16}} miles (9.5 furlongs)\n| surface       = Dirt\n| track         = left-handed\n| qualification = Three-years-old\n| weight        = \n| purse         = \n}}\n\nThe '''Reapers Stakes''' was an American [[Thoroughbred horse race]] run annually at [[Sheepshead Bay Race Track]] in [[Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn]]. Held in September, the race was open to three-year-olds of either sex. It was run on dirt over a distance of 1 3/16 miles except for 1903 when it was set at 1 3/8 miles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1900s/drf1907090501/drf1907090501_4_2 |title=Condensed History of the Reapers Stakes |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1907-09-05 |accessdate=2018-12-21}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, 1880 the Sheepshead Bay facility hosted its first day of [[Thoroughbred racing]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coney Island Jockey Club; Programme for the September Meeting |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1879/09/03/archives/coney-island-jockey-club-programme-for-the-september-meeting-a.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 3, 1879 |page=3 |accessdate=2010-01-16}}</ref> Success made the addition of more stakes races possible and in 1887 the Reapers Stakes had its inaugural running. That race was won by [[Belvidere (horse)|Belvidere]], a colt owned by the [[Preakness Stud#James Galway|Preakness Stables]] of James Galway, a successful [[Wholesaling|wholesaler]] of [[grocery store]] products and a [[Glossary of North American horse racing#Steward|Steward]] of [[The Jockey Club]]. The final running took place in 1907 and was won by the 20:1 outsider, Blue Book.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/20309048 |title=Blue Book; 20 To 1, Wins The Reapers |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1907-09-06 |accessdate=2018-12-22}}</ref>\n\n== Demise of the Reapers Stakes ==\nAfter years of uncertainty, on June 11, 1908 the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] controlled [[New York Legislature]] under [[Governor of New York|Governor]] [[Charles Evans Hughes]] passed the [[Hart-Agnew Law|Hart-Agnew]] anti-betting legislation with penalties allowing for [[Fine (penalty)|fines]] and up to a year in [[prison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1900s/drf1908011801/drf1908011801_1_7 |title=Penalties in the New York Bills |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date=1908-01-18|accessdate=2018-10-26}}</ref> The owners of Sheepshead Bay Race Track, and other racing facilities in New York State, struggled to stay in business without income from betting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1908/09/01/archives/keep-up-betting-ban-strict-enforcement-of-the-law-at-sheepshead-bay.html  |title=Keep Up Betting Ban |publisher=New York Times |date=1908-09-01 |accessdate=2018-11-06}}</ref> Racetrack operators had no choice but to drastically reduce the [[Purse distribution|purse money]] being paid out which resulted in the Reapers Stakes being dropped from the 1908 schedule to enable a redistribution of funds to the most high profile races.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://drf.uky.edu/catalog/1910s/drf1910071601/drf1910071601_1_7 |title=Striking Falling off in Value of Ten Greatest Stakes |publisher=Daily Racing Form at University of Kentucky Archives |date= 1910-07-16 |accessdate=2018-10-15}}</ref> Further restrictive legislation was passed by the New York Legislature in 1910 which deepened the financial crisis for track operators and led to a complete shut down of racing across the state during 1911 and 1912. When a Court ruling saw racing return in 1913 it was too late for the Sheepshead Bay horse racing facility and it never reopened.\n\n==Records==\n'''Speed record:''' (new track record)\n* 1:59.40 - Heno (1902)\n\n'''Most wins by a [[jockey]]:'''\n* 3 - [[Fred Taral]] (1891, 1896, 1898)\n\n'''Most wins by a [[Horse trainer|trainer]]:'''\n* 2 - [[John W. Rogers (horse trainer)|John W. Rogers]] (1889, 1894)\n* 2 - [[Charles S. Littlefield Sr.]] (1898, 1901)\n\n'''Most wins by an owner:'''\n* 2 - [[Preakness Stud#James Galway|Preakness Stables]] (1887, 1897)\n* 2 - [[Rancocas Farm#Pierre Lorillard IV|Rancocas Stable]] (1892, 1900)\n* 2 - [[Charles S. Littlefield Sr.]] (1898, 1901)\n\n==Winners==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|- \n! style=\"width:30px\" | Year<br>\n! style=\"width:110px\" | Winner<br>\n! style=\"width:20px\" | Age<br>\n! style=\"width:110px\" | Jockey<br>\n! style=\"width:120px\" | Trainer<br>\n! Owner<br>\n! style=\"width:25px\" | Dist.<br> <span style=\"font-size:70%\">([[Mile|Miles]])</span>\n! style=\"width:25px\" | Time<br>\n! style=\"width:25px\" | Win[[United States dollar|$]]\n|-\n|align=center|1907\n|Blue Book\n|align=center|3\n|R. Lowe\n|Stephen J. Lawler\n|James F. Carroll\n|align=center|1<span style=\"font-size:85%\">{{Frac|3|16}} M</span>\n|align=center|2:05.00\n|align=center|$3,375\n|-\n|align=center|1906\n|Entr\u00e9e\n|align=center|3\n|[[Herman Radtke]]\n|Thomas H. McCreery\n|Frederick A. Johnson\n|align=center|1<span style=\"font-size:85%\">{{Frac|3|16}} M</span>\n|align=center|2:00.60\n|align=center|$3,475\n|-\n|align=center|1905\n|Coy Maid\n|align=center|3\n|[[Willie Knapp]]\n|John I. Smith\n|Kenilworth Stable (Frederick C. McLewee)\n|align=center|1<span style=\"font-size:85%\">{{Frac|3|16}} M</span>\n|align=center|2:01.60\n|align=center|$3,275\n|-\n|align=center|1904\n|Aurumaster\n|align=center|3\n|William Crimmins\n|[[Matthew Feakes]]\n|H. 